example.p:
\(M=[\mathcal{P}\{1,2,3\};\cap  ]\) is isomorphic to \(M_2=\left[\mathbb{Z}_2^3;\cdot \right]\), where the operation in \(M_2\) is componentwise mod 2 multiplication. A translation rule is that if \(A\subseteq \{1,2,3\}\), then it is translated to \(\left(d_1,d_2,d_3\right)\) where 
d_i=\left\{
\begin{array}{cc}
 1 & \textrm{ if } i\in A \\
 0 & \textrm{ if } i\notin A \\
\end{array}
\right. 

 Two cases of how this translation rule works are:


\begin{array}{lr}
			\begin{array}{c}
			\{1, 2, 3\}\quad\textrm{ is the identity for } M_1\\
			 \updownarrow   \\
			(1,1,1) \quad\textrm{ is the identity for }M_2\\
			\end{array} 
	&     
		\begin{array}{c}
		 \{1, 2\}\cap \{ 2, 3\}=\{2\}\\
			\updownarrow \\       
		(1, 1, 0) \cdot  (0, 1, 1) = (0, 1, 0)\\
		\end{array}\\
               \quad
\end{array}
.

li.p:
The identity of \(\mathbb{N}^{\mathbb{N}}\) is the identity function \(i:\mathbb{N}\to \mathbb{N}\) defined by \(i(a) = a\), \(\forall a\in \mathbb{N}\).  If \(a \in \mathbb{N}\), \(i(a) = a \leq  a\), thus the identity of \(\mathbb{N}^{\mathbb{N}}\) is in \(S_1\). However, the image of 1 under any
function in \(S_2\) is 2, and thus the identity of \(\mathbb{N}^{\mathbb{N}}\) is not in \(S_2\), so \(S_2\) is not a submonoid. The composition of any two functions in \(S_1\),  f and g, will be a function in \(S_1\):

\begin{split}
(f\circ g)(n) & = f(g(n)) \leq g(n)\textrm{      since } f \textrm{ is in } S_1\\
		& \leq n\textrm{       since } g \textrm{ is in } S_1 \Rightarrow f \circ g \in S_1
\end{split}

and the two conditions of a submonoid are satisfied and \(S_1\) is a submonoid of  \(\mathbb{N}^{\mathbb{N}}\).

answer.p:
Let \(f, g, h \in M\), and \(a \in B\).
\begin{split} ((f*g)*h)(a) & = (f*g)(a) \land h(a)\\ & = (f(a)\land g(a))\land h(a)\\ & = f(a) \land ( g(a) \land h(a))\\ & = f(a) \land (g * h)(a)\\ & = (f * (g * h))(a)\\ \end{split}
Therefore \((f * g) * h =f * (g * h)\) and \(*\) is associative.
